{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:34:16.118234+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "[{\"type\":\"file\",\"size\":588,\"name\":\"test_limiter.py\",\"path\":\"tests/test_limiter.py\",\"sha\":\"509f09595050531b594b7c3376c3557d8e41979e\",\"url\":\"https://api.github.com/repos/rpnr-bench/T12_R01/contents/tests/test_limiter.py?ref=154e9f2eaabdb2ca3643af5d3548cf3433dded52\",\"git_url\":\"https://api.github.com/repos/rpnr-bench/T12_R01/git/blobs/509f09595050531b594b7c3376c3557d8e41979e\",\"html_url\":\"https://github.com/rpnr-bench/T12_R01/blob/154e9f2eaabdb2ca3643af5d3548cf3433dded52/tests/test_limiter.py\",\"download_url\":\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rpnr-bench/T12_R01/154e9f2eaabdb2ca3643af5d3548cf3433dded52/tests/test_limiter.py\"}]", "id": "lc_98037bb5-c0a6-4fbf-a78e-fb8b56a237cf"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "65b78bff-6cee-47d9-b2cb-f26c3afb77cf", "tool_call_id": "call_db051bc5f0404d91ba517242", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:34:45.074099+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Now I have all the code I need. Here's a thorough step-by-step explanation.\n\n---\n\n## `Limiter.check()` — Full Walkthrough\n\n### Python Side (`limiter.py`)\n\n**Signature:** `def check(self, key: str, cost: int = 1) -> Tuple[bool, int]`\n\n**Inputs:**\n| Parameter | Type | Default | Meaning |\n|-----------|------|---------|---------|\n| `key` | `str` | — | An arbitrary logical key identifying the resource/subject being rate-limited (e.g. a user ID, IP, endpoint). |\n| `cost` | `int` | `1` | How many tokens this operation costs. |\n\n**Return value:** A tuple `(allowed, remaining)`:\n- `allowed` (`bool`) — `True` if the request was permitted, `False` if it was denied.\n- `remaining` (`int`) — The number of whole tokens left in the bucket after this call (floored to an integer).\n\n**Step 1 — Build the Redis key**\n\n```python\nbucket_key = f\"rl:{{{key}}}\"\n```\n\nThe key is prefixed with `rl:` and the user-supplied `key` is wrapped in `{}` curly braces. The curly braces act as a **Redis Cluster hash tag**, ensuring all operations for the same logical key land on the same cluster shard.\n\n**Step 2 — Execute the Lua script atomically via `EVALSHA`**\n\n```python\nresult = self._r.evalsha(\n    self._sha,       # SHA of the pre-loaded Lua script\n    1,               # number of KEYS arguments\n    bucket_key,      # KEYS[1]\n    str(self._capacity),  # ARGV[1]\n    str(self._refill),    # ARGV[2]\n    str(cost),            # ARGV[3]\n)\n```\n\nAll rate-limiting logic — the refill, the consume, and the state update — happens **atomically** inside Redis via a single `EVALSHA` call. No other client can interleave with it.\n\n**Step 3 — Unpack and return**\n\n```python\nallowed   = bool(result[0])\nremaining = int(result[1])\nreturn allowed, remaining\n```\n\n---\n\n### Redis / Lua Side (`bucket.lua`)\n\nThe Lua script implements a classic **token-bucket** algorithm. Here is every step it performs:\n\n**Step L1 — Read the current wall-clock time**\n\n```lua\nlocal now_ms = redis.call(\"TIME\")\nnow_ms = now_ms[1] * 1000 + math.floor(now_ms[2] / 1000)\n```\n\nUses the Redis server's own clock (`TIME` command, returns `[seconds, microseconds]`) and converts it to **milliseconds**. This avoids any clock-skew issues between application servers.\n\n**Step L2 — Load persisted bucket state**\n\n```lua\nlocal state   = redis.call(\"HMGET\", key, \"tokens\", \"ts\")\nlocal tokens  = tonumber(state[1])\nlocal last_ts = tonumber(state[2])\n```\n\nReads two fields from a Redis **hash** at `KEYS[1]`:\n| Field | Meaning |\n|-------|---------|\n| `tokens` | The token level at the time of the last call (stored as a string-encoded float). |\n| `ts` | The Redis-server timestamp (ms) at the time of the last call. |\n\n**Step L3 — First-call initialisation**\n\n```lua\nif tokens == nil or last_ts == nil then\n    tokens  = capacity\n    last_ts = now_ms\nend\n```\n\nIf the hash doesn't exist yet (first request for this key), the bucket starts **completely full** at `capacity`.\n\n**Step L4 — Refill tokens based on elapsed time**\n\n```lua\nlocal elapsed_sec = math.max(0, (now_ms - last_ts) / 1000.0)\ntokens = math.min(capacity, tokens + elapsed_sec * refill)\n```\n\nTokens are added proportional to the wall-clock time elapsed since the last call, at a rate of `refill` tokens/second. The result is capped at `capacity` (tokens never accumulate beyond the bucket's maximum).\n\n**Step L5 — Consume tokens (or deny)**\n\n```lua\nlocal allowed = 0\nif tokens >= cost then\n    tokens = tokens - cost\n    allowed = 1\nend\n```\n\nIf there are enough tokens, they are subtracted and `allowed` is set to `1`. Otherwise `allowed` stays `0` and the token level is unchanged (the request is denied, no tokens are spent).\n\n**Step L6 — Persist updated state back to Redis**\n\n```lua\nredis.call(\"HMSET\", key, \"tokens\", tostring(tokens), \"ts\", tostring(now_ms))\n```\n\nWrites the **new** token level and the **current** timestamp back into the hash. This is the side effect that survives across calls.\n\n**Step L7 — Set / refresh a TTL**\n\n```lua\nlocal ttl = math.max(60, math.ceil(capacity / refill * 10))\nredis.call(\"EXPIRE\", key, ttl)\n```\n\nThe TTL is calculated as **10× the time it takes to fully refill the bucket** (i.e. `capacity / refill * 10` seconds), with a floor of **60 seconds**. This ensures idle buckets are eventually garbage-collected from Redis, while active buckets never expire prematurely.\n\n**Step L8 — Return result**\n\n```lua\nreturn {allowed, math.floor(tokens)}\n```\n\nReturns two integers: the allow/deny flag (0 or 1) and the **floored** remaining token count.\n\n---\n\n### Summary of Redis Side Effects\n\n| What | Where | Detail |\n|------|-------|--------|\n| **Hash fields written** | `rl:{<key>}` → `tokens` | Current (post-consume) token level, stored as a string. |\n| **Hash fields written** | `rl:{<key>}` → `ts` | Wall-clock timestamp (ms) of this update. |\n| **TTL set/refreshed** | `rl:{<key>}` | `EXPIRE` with a TTL of `max(60, ceil(capacity / refill * 10))` seconds. |\n\nIf the hash didn't exist before, it is **created**. If it already existed, its fields and TTL are **overwritten/refreshed**.\n\n---\n\n### Concrete Example\n\nWith `capacity=10`, `refill_per_sec=2`, and `cost=1`:\n\n1. **First call** → bucket initialised to 10 tokens. One is consumed → `(True, 9)`.\n2. **Immediate second call** (0 ms later) → no refill, 9 ≥ 1 → `(True, 8)`.\n3. **After 1 second** → 8 + 1×2 = 10 (capped), consume 1 → `(True, 9)`.\n4. **10 rapid calls** → drains to 0, next call → `(False, 0)`.\n5. **After 5 seconds of waiting** → 0 + 5×2 = 10, consume 1 → `(True, 9)`.\n6. **After 1 hour of no calls** → the key has expired via TTL; next call re-initialises to capacity.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 1594, "prompt_tokens": 5708, "total_tokens": 7302, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 21, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 5312, "cache_write_tokens": 0, "video_tokens": 0}, "cost": 0, "is_byok": true, "cost_details": {"upstream_inference_cost": 0.0015781632, "upstream_inference_prompt_cost": 0.0001913832, "upstream_inference_completions_cost": 0.00138678}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-20260422", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "gen-1780864456-rvNBfEuAaMMHJ3mPzfyy", "finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea3cb-15b6-79c0-9307-8cc0d6c03e4e-0", "tool_calls": [], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 5708, "output_tokens": 1594, "total_tokens": 7302, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 5312}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 21}}}}]}}}
